{"questionId":"17126","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">In a classical model of the singly-ionized helium atom, a single electron orbits the nucleus in a circular orbit of radius <em>r</em>.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/6616348d2ee9df8cf2261a18502b031373cbb5d9.png\" width=\"249\" height=\"248\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Hence, deduce that the total energy of the electron is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>TOT</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math>.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">uses (a)(i) to state&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;<em><strong>OR&nbsp;</strong></em>states&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math>&nbsp;✔</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">adds&nbsp;«&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>TOT</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math>» to get the result ✔</span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17126","referenceCode":"19N.2.HL.TZ0.8a(ii)","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Hence, deduce that the total energy of the electron is given by ETOT=-ke2r.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields","10.2 – Fields at work","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}